Unless they, like, 20 years old. From gone so far, I respect to all those people that got off the plane. And as for you that stayed on the plane, I'm sorry. I was so upset by this when I woke up that I didn't even bother putting on a shirt. So I apologize if for some reason you're unaware, part of Maui, specifically Lahaina, is currently on fire. This is what was and is still currently happening in Maui. There was a wild brush fire that, combined with a Hurricane, started spreading all those fire embers all over the place, spreading the fire. I mean, look, that tree just caught on fire. Yeah, this isn't a scene from Stranger Things. This is literally Lahaina. See that? Those are people's heads floating in the water, because people are literally jumping in the ocean to escape the scorching fires. Like, if you take a close look at this video, this person who's recording is standing in his neighborhood, and he's completely covered on all sides with scorching fire. These are people's homes, neighborhoods, and whole livelihoods. And 36 people have already been confirmed to have lost their lives to the fire and Hurricane, and that number is just going To go up. Because look at all of this and notice the lack of resources and firefighters. That's because Hawaii Maui is an island with very limited resources. Look at this. Thousands of people are displaced from their homes, which means that they're going to need temporary shelter. So why would you fly into an island with limited resources, where they need more resources, to help all the displaced victims, and selfishly go there for your own enjoyment? There's literally no reason why anyone should be flying to Hawaii right now, because even the neighboring islands, those resources are needed for these thousands of victims. Imagine being the person who has a friend who just lost their home and members of their family in a fire, and then going over their house and going, hey, man, you wanna hang out? column10: Is an absolute tragedy. If you really care about Native Hawaiians, you will stay out of Hawaii. Native Hawaiians have spoken. They don't want outsiders on their islands. Considering what's taken place in Maui, it's important that we listen to their voices. So why are Native Hawaiians so adamant about staying out of their homelands? For one, the tourism industry does nothing to help Native Hawaiians. In Oahu, there are 0 owned native hotels. All that tourism money goes to multinational corporations who make millions off of exploiting Hawaiian culture. The tourism industry is not a friend to native Hawaiians. And it goes deeper. The Hawaiian Islands represent a complex history of settler colonialism. The Hawaiian Kingdom was overthrown by a group of non native elites. These Howleys had no regard for Hawaiian sovereignty. They were driven by a desire to capitalize on the island's abundant resources. Let's not forget the Hawaiian Islands are stolen lands. And it only gets worse. Native Hawaiians have experienced decades of cultural appropriation. Native Hawaiians have a beautiful and unique culture. However, their life ways have been exploited and appropriated by multinational corporations for financial gain. This has LED to a warped view of Hawaiian culture, and many outsiders show nothing but disrespect for the sacred places. For Native Hawaiians, decades of tourism and agro business has done incredible damage to these fragile ecosystems. This, combined with climate change, has LED to the destruction of Maui. The town of Lahaina doesn't even exist any Longer and hundreds of people are still missing. This is not the time to visit Hawaii and be a tourist if you care about indigenous rights and sovereignty. Let's do our part in respect the wishes of our Native Hawaiian relatives. And all you howlies out there, show some respect and stay out of Hawaii. We don't even know how many lives have been lost to these wildfires. So let's give Native Hawaiian some time to grieve and support them from afar. If you want to support the relief effort, check out the link in my bio. And remember, it's time to learn, listen, and respect the wishes of our Native Hawaiian relatives.

column10: Good morning, everybody. Um, I have a very, very important announcement for you guys about the Lahaina fires. So right now, they, as I mentioned before, have been overwhelmed with supplies. The biggest need on the island is housing right now. We have so many people displaced with nowhere to go, who are still not even in hotels or Airbnbs. They are still sleeping on the streets, they're sleeping on the beach, they're sleeping under trees. They don't even have tents and tarps. Um, we have sent a lot of those things, so that tells you just how many people have been displaced by this. Now I have people on the ground in Lahaina, my friends and family, who are reporting to me on what is happening, and what I have heard is very disturbing. So apparently, as of today, the governor has opened access to Lahaina on the roads to everyone, including non residents of Lahaina. This is a massive problem. There are so many people who have still been waiting to get back in and survey their properties and survey the damage and seeing what's happening. And now we're going to be letting in dark tourists. Now, granted, this is going to be good to help a lot of the supplies that need to get through in, but the fact that they are letting anybody in right now is. Is alarming. Um, there are still entire neighborhoods that smell of death. There are still bodies being found, and Identified. This is not the time to be having the town open. But worst of all, the. The biggest problem with this is it now means tourism is going to return to this area when it is not ready yet. I have a good friend who is being put up by an Airbnb owned by somebody out of country. I won't say exactly where this person is from because I do not want to risk repercussions for my friend and them potentially losing their place that they have sheltered. Right now. They have just been notified that if a tourist books the Airbnb, they have to leave. This is beyond, beyond fucked up. These are people who have no place to go. If you, if you own an Airbnb in Maui, you should not be renting it to anybody. You should be volunteering it to the people who are displaced. If you have to rent it, if you really need money, rented to the people who are displaced at a reasonable rate. This is not a time to be gaining money and profit for yourself out of country. You are not even a resident of Lahaina. This money that is coming in is not benefiting the people. It is not benefiting of those in need. column6: We can all learn something from the Maui fires that can benefit us. column10: with the fires in Maui a lot of the content out there is very doom and gloom how horrible it is what caused it different theories about why that is how horrible the government response is a lot of negativity and for sure there's a time and a place for that conversation but there are also some lessons to be taken from the event at large that can benefit your life the most important is that nothing really matters except how much love and happiness you're feeling on a day to day basis like your material possessions that doesn't matter at all and it can disappear within a day and all that you can carry with you if something like that happens in your life or after you die is how much love you've had in your life and how much you've been able to share with others and the experiences you have on a day to day basis and the more we can realize that that is what needs to be appreciated in our life and not the material things the happier we're gonna be

column6: Pray for Ohio Crews began releasing toxic chemicals into the air from five derailed tanker cars that were in danger of exploding Monday after warning residents near the Ohio-Pennsvlvania state line to leave immediately or face the possibility of death. Flames and black smoke billowed high into the sky from the derailment site late in the afternoon, about an hour after authorities said the controlled release would begin. The Ohio Emergency Management Agency confirmed the release was underway. Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine earlier ordered evacuations in the area of the derailment that has been smoldering since Friday night. Authorities believe most, if not all, residents in the danger zone had left but they were knocking on doors one more time before releasing the vinyl chloride inside the cars, he said. "You need to leave, you just need to leave. This is a matter of life and death," DeWine said at press conference. Officials warned the controlled burn would send phosgene and hydrogen chloride into the air. Phosgene is a highly toxic gas that can cause vomiting and breathing trouble and was used as a weapon in World War #tanker #train #derailed #traintracks #sad #disaster #ohio #accident

column6: We have such an amazing network of supporters and friends, but unfortunately find ourselves having to ask for some serious help. The catastrophic flooding has seriously affected our hay storage and pastures and washed out an entire road. Our horses are all safe and dry, but the costs to repair this will be astronomical. Hay will also be in extremely short supply across the entire state after this event, and it's the time of year when our lofts are empty as we prepare for the new years hay.  We desperately need monetary donations, hay donations, or volunteer help to put up the hay we can find and start to repair once flood waters go down.  https://www.gerdasequinerescue.org/donate #rescue #vermontstrong #vermontflood #rescuehorses #help #everylittlebitcounts #gerdasequinerescue

column10: Acapoco, Mexico just witnessed the closest thing to a surprise category 5 Hurricane in unprecedented event in modern forecasting. Early Tuesday morning, Hurricane Otis was forecast to landfalling Mexico as a tropical storm with sustain winds under 73 miles per hour. Just 20 hours later, Otis became a full fledged category 5 Hurricane with sustained winds of 165 miles per hour. This left resident and Acapulco with very little notice that the most powerful category of tropical cyclone was about to usher in devastating storm surge and extremely powerful winds. column10: The most powerful storm to have ever hit Mexico's Pacific coast has just passed. And the footage of the aftermath is absolutely mind blowing. Videos from the 21st floor of a beachfront hotel in Acapulco show apocalyptic scenes. Also. Man recording says in disbelief this cannot be possible. Other videos show tennis courts covered in debris, hotels and high rises completely stripped of their exterior, boats in absolute ruins along the coastline that was battered by 160 mile per hour winds. This is the before and after image of a brand new 130 million dollar luxury high rise in Acapulco. But the wildest part about this storm is the reason you probably didn't even know that it happened. Since seeing the Category 5 Hurricane make. And forecasters and meteorologists are baffled at how they did not see it coming. The city of one million people were warned that it would just be a tropical. But the usually reliable computer models failed to predict its explosive intensification from a Category 1 to a category 5 in just 12 hours. And then after it hit, all the power, internet service and communication is being down. So we haven't been able to see the full extent of the destruction until now. At least twenty seven people have been killed. 80% of the city's hotels and all the power lines have been destroyed. And even the airport's control tower has been torn apart. There are still so many unanswered questions about this. But of course As we know more, I'll keep you guys updated.
